nd Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Glanville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): of Norman origin, a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, named from an ancient Germanic personal name of uncertain form and meaning + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. This name has frequently been confused with <b>Glanfield</b>, a habitational name from Glanvill Farm in Devon, Clanville in Somerset and Hampshire, or Clanfield in Hampshire, or from some other place likewise named with Old English <i>clǣne</i> ‘clean’ (i.e. free of brambles and undergrowth) + <i>feld</i> ‘pasture, open country’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Glanville was born about 1184, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam de Glanville, was 34 and his mother, Marie de Vatteville, was 26. He had at least 1 son with Karmine Manneville. He died in 1230, at the age of 47."},"et":{"Abt 1184–1230":"umbes 1184–1230","1184–1230":"1184–1230","1198–Female":"1198–Surnud","1217–1272":"1217–1272","1152–1208":"1152–1208","1160–1215":"1160–1215","1217":"1217","Abt 1184":"umbes 118